¶

Project scope¶

In order to anticipate the facies (lithology rock type) in the oil and gas field and to create forecasts for additional wells based on the model, I decided to examine the data from the drilled wells and utilize machine learning in this project. Facies is a key indicator of where oil and gas will be found, and problems arise when there is insufficient information from rock samples. One of the better methods for interpreting for Facie lithology rock type involves using extra data and a machine learning technique:

  • Project overview: Characterizing facies is one of the most important tasks for geoscientists engaged in development and exploratory projects. The sedimentary facies is a reflection of the physical, chemical, and biological circumstances that a unit experienced throughout the sedimentation process. In order to develop a model that will forecast the facies-lithology rocktype for additional wells, I will in this project study the data from 4 wells as well as the well log information.
  • Problem proposition: In order to build a model for future facies forecast for another well without facies interpretation, machine learning algorithms (Neural Networks) are trained to predict facies from well log data utilizing data from continuous logs (NPHI, RHOB, VCL, DT & and discrete log: Facies).
  • Metrics: In this study, we used recall, accuracy, and F1-Score performance indicators as a categorization technique.

The performance metric's key In this work, classification metrics from the ideas of True Positive, True Negative, False Positive, and False Negative were employed to verify the model, including accuracy, recall, and F1-Score.

Jusity the selection of Recall, Accuracy and F1 score for this problem (add more information)¶

In this study, we used recall, accuracy, and F1-Score performance indicators as a categorization technique.

  • Precision, recall, and the F1-Score are important classification metrics that were employed in this study to evaluate the model.
  • These metrics are derived from the ideas of True Positive, True Negative, False Positive, and False Negative.

Learn more about the measurements in the dataset:

  • Litho_Facies: 0 is Shale, 1 is Sand
  • Formation: Well type A
  • GR: Gamma Rays from the Gamma Ray Log Tool, which tracks the formation's emission of gamma rays. Due to the presence of radioactive minerals, shale has greater Gamma Ray.
  • VCL: Volume of Clay
  • NPHI: Nuclear Porosity locating the hydrocarbon-bearing zone, calculating porosity, etc.
  • RHOB: The mass-to-volume ratio of a measured interval serves as the basis for calculating the bulk density (rhob or b) of a formation.
  • DT: Sonic
  • PHI/PHIE: effective porosity

"""
Well logs plot
"""
f_labels = ["Shale", "Sand"]
f_colors = ["#d05430", "#36b8e3"]


def log_plot_facies(logs, facies_colors):
    
    # To sort log by depth
    logs = logs.sort_values(by="Depth")
    
    facies_cmap = colors.ListedColormap(
            facies_colors[0:len(facies_colors)+1],
        "indexed"
    )
    
    ztop = 3100
    zbot = 3800
    
    cluster = np.repeat(
        np.expand_dims(
            df["Litho_Facies"].values,
            1
        ),
        100,
        1
    )
    
    f, ax = plt.subplots(
        nrows=1,
        ncols=6,
        figsize=(8, 12)
    )
    ax[0].plot(
        df.GR,
        df.Depth,
        "-g"
    )
    ax[1].plot(
        df.VCL,
        df.Depth,
        "-"
    )
    ax[2].plot(
        df.NPHI,
        df.Depth,
        "-",
        color="0.5"
    )
    ax[3].plot(
        df.RHOB,
        df.Depth,
        "-",
        color="r"
    )
    ax[4].plot(
        df.DT,
        df.Depth,
        "-",
        color="purple"
    )
    
    im = ax[5].imshow(
        cluster,
        interpolation="none",
        aspect="auto",
        cmap=facies_cmap,
        vmin=0,
        vmax=1
    )
    
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax[5])
    cax = divider.append_axes(
        "right",
        size="20%",
        pad=0.05
    )
    cbar = plt.colorbar(
        im,
        cax=cax
    )
    cbar.set_label(
        (18*" ").join([" Sand ", " Shale "])
    )
    cbar.set_ticks(
        range(0,1))
    cbar.set_ticklabels("")
    
    for i in range(len(ax)-1):
        ax[i].set_ylim(ztop,zbot)
        ax[i].invert_yaxis()
        ax[i].grid()
        ax[i].locator_params(
            axis="x",
            nbins=3
        )
    
    ax[0].set_xlabel("GR")
    ax[0].set_xlim(0, 150)
    
    ax[1].set_xlabel("VCL")
    ax[1].set_xlim(0, 1)
    
    ax[2].set_xlabel("NPHI")
    ax[2].set_xlim(0.1, 0.3)
    
    ax[3].set_xlabel("RHOB")
    ax[3].set_xlim(2, 3)
    
    ax[4].set_xlabel("DT")
    ax[4].set_xlim(60, 150)
    
    ax[5].set_xlabel("Litho_Facies")
    ax[5].set_xlim(0, 1)
    
    ax[1].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[2].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[3].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[4].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[5].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[5].set_xticklabels([])

2. Preprocess data¶

2.1 Robust Scaler - Feature Transforming¶

Refer documentation of Robust Scaler

Algorithms, and techniques (add more information)¶

Scale features using statistics that are robust to outliers.

This Scaler removes the median and scales the data according to the quantile range (defaults to IQR: Interquartile Range). The IQR is the range between the 1st quartile (25th quantile) and the 3rd quartile (75th quantile).

Centering and scaling happen independently on each feature by computing the relevant statistics on the samples in the training set. Median and interquartile range are then stored to be used on later data using the transform method.

Standardization of a dataset is a common requirement for many machine learning estimators. Typically this is done by removing the mean and scaling to unit variance. However, outliers can often influence the sample mean / variance in a negative way. In such cases, the median and the interquartile range often give better results.

"""
To create standardized data, transform the train dataset.
"""
X_train_scaled = robust_scaler.transform(X_train) 

scaled_median = np.median(
        X_train_scaled,
        axis=0
)
scaled_iqr = np.percentile(X_train_scaled, 75, axis=0) - np.percentile(X_train_scaled, 25, axis=0)
print("Scaled median : %s " % scaled_median)
print("Scaled IQR : %s " % scaled_iqr)

print("Original median : %s " % robust_scaler.center_)
print("Original IQR : %s " % robust_scaler.scale_)

"""
Scale the test data using the metrics discovered from the practice dataset.
"""
X_test_scaled = robust_scaler.transform(X_test)

scaled_test_data = (
    np.percentile(X_test_scaled, 75, axis=0) - np.percentile(X_test_scaled, 25, axis=0)
)
print("IQR scaled test data: %s " % scaled_test_data)

def facies_plot_comparation(logs, compare, facies_colors):

    logs = logs.sort_values(by="Depth")
    facies_cmap = colors.ListedColormap(
        facies_colors[0:len(facies_colors)],
        "indexed"
    )

    ztop=3100
    zbot=3800
    
    cluster1 = np.repeat(
        np.expand_dims(well_checking["Litho_Facies"].values, 1),
        100,
        1
    )
    cluster2 = np.repeat(
        np.expand_dims(well_checking[compare].values, 1),
        100,
        1
    )
    f, ax = plt.subplots(
        nrows=1,
        ncols=7,
        figsize=(9, 12)
    )
    ax[0].plot(
        well_checking.GR,
        well_checking.Depth,
        "-g"
    )
    ax[1].plot(
        well_checking.VCL,
        well_checking.Depth,
        "-")
    ax[2].plot(
        well_checking.NPHI,
        well_checking.Depth,
        "-",
        color="0.5"
    )
    ax[3].plot(
        well_checking.RHOB,
        well_checking.Depth,
        "-",
        color="r"
    )
    ax[4].plot(
        well_checking.DT,
        well_checking.Depth,
        "-",
        color="black"
    )
    im1 = ax[5].imshow(
        cluster1,
        interpolation="none",
        aspect="auto",
        cmap=facies_cmap,
        vmin=0,
        vmax=1
    )
    im2 = ax[6].imshow(
        cluster2,
        interpolation="none",
        aspect="auto",
        cmap=facies_cmap,
        vmin=0,
        vmax=1
    )
    
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax[6])
    cax = divider.append_axes(
        "right",
        size="20%",
        pad=0.05
    )
    cbar = plt.colorbar(
        im2,
        cax=cax
    )
    cbar.set_label(
        (17*" ").join([" Sand "," Shale "]))
    cbar.set_ticks(range(0,1))
    cbar.set_ticklabels("")
    
    for i in range(len(ax)-2):
        ax[i].set_ylim(
            ztop,
            zbot
        )
        ax[i].invert_yaxis()
        ax[i].grid()
        ax[i].locator_params(
            axis="x",
            nbins=3
        )
    
    ax[0].set_xlabel("GR")
    ax[0].set_xlim(0,150)
    
    ax[1].set_xlabel("VCL")
    ax[1].set_xlim(0,1)
    
    ax[2].set_xlabel("NPHI")
    ax[2].set_xlim(0.1,0.3)
    
    ax[3].set_xlabel("RHOB")
    ax[3].set_xlim(2,3)
    
    ax[4].set_xlabel("DT")
    ax[4].set_xlim(60,150)
    
    ax[5].set_xlabel("Litho_Facies")
    ax[5].set_xlim(0,1)
    
    ax[6].set_xlabel(compare)
    ax[6].set_xlim(0,1)
    
    ax[1].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[2].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[3].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[4].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[5].set_yticklabels([])
    ax[5].set_xticklabels([])
    ax[6].set_xticklabels([])

Summary

  • According to the blind test, we can see that the precision is an excellent match with the real data when the model is used to compare with test data that actually contains the data.

  • Because the ANN model lacks data, it will be a suitable method to use for forecasting facies in additional wells.

  • Good match determined by train, test, and prediction values obtained from the density visualization.

  • To improve the results, we may concentrate on two key areas in the phases that follow: Adjust model parameters, include new samples of data into the models, and compare using more ML techniques
